Milestone report: Exploratory Data analysis of English corpus

Sergio Garcia Busto

2022-10-04

Introduction

Modern keyboards have built-in text predictor algorithms in order to ease the writing process of the user. Besides, these algorithms are also used in a variety of industries. The objective of the Capstone Project is to predict the next word based on the preceding word(s) using a large text dataset collected from Twitter, blogs, and news (raw data: https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/dsscapstone/dataset/Coursera-SwiftKey.zip. This report intends to outline the Exploratory Data Analysis performed prior to building a prediction model. The datasets from three sources (Twitter, blogs and news) will be briefly explored and data will be combined, tokenized and analysed via unigrams and bigrams.

Data wrangling and tokenization

Data loading and corpus creation is done as a first step:

#Data loading and corpus creation
twitter<-read_lines("en_US.twitter.txt")
## Warning: One or more parsing issues, see `problems()` for details
tw<-data.table(twitter)
tw.df<-data.frame(tw)
tw.s<-sample(tw.df$twitter, 15000)
tw.c<-corpus(tw.s)

news<-read_lines("en_US.news.txt")
nw<-data.table(news)
nw.fr<-data.frame(nw)
nw.s<-sample(nw.fr$news, 15000)
nw.c<-corpus(nw.s)

blogs<-read_lines("en_US.blogs.txt")
bl<-data.table(blogs)
bl.fr<-data.frame(bl)
bl.s<-sample(bl.fr$blogs, 15000)
bl.c<-corpus(bl.s)

Document names should also be updated for combining datasets from different sources into a big corpus:

docnames(bl.c)<-paste("bl", 1:15000, sep = ".")
docnames(nw.c)<-paste("nw", 1:15000, sep = ".")
docnames(tw.c)<-paste("tw", 1:15000, sep = ".")

Moreover, a list of profanities is loaded for removal during tokenization.

bad<-read.table("list.txt", sep = "\n")
bad<-as.character(bad$V1)

Data merging and tokenization of the total corpus is conducted below to form two objects, with and without common English words. The tokens with common words will be eventually used, as these words will also need to be predicted. The source will also be included for comparison.

#tokenizing total, appointing source for comparison
total.corpus<-tw.c+nw.c+bl.c
docvars(total.corpus, "source")<-c(rep("twitter",15000), rep("news", 15000), rep("blogs", 15000))
tok<-total.corpus %>%
  tokens(remove_punct = TRUE,
         remove_symbols = TRUE,
         remove_numbers = TRUE,
         remove_url = TRUE,
         split_hyphens = TRUE) %>%
  tokens_remove(bad) %>%
  tokens_keep(pattern = "^[a-zA-Z]+$", valuetype = "regex")

tok.st<-total.corpus %>%
  tokens(remove_punct = TRUE,
         remove_symbols = TRUE,
         remove_numbers = TRUE,
         remove_url = TRUE,
         split_hyphens = TRUE) %>%
  tokens_remove(bad) %>%
  tokens_remove(stopwords("english")) %>%
  tokens_keep(pattern = "^[a-zA-Z]+$", valuetype = "regex")

Finally, unigrams and bigrams (and corresponding document feature matrices) will be created for analysis.

#unigrams and dfms
unig_tok<-tokens_ngrams(tok, n=1)
unig.st_tok<-tokens_ngrams(tok.st, n=1)
unig_dfm<-dfm(unig_tok)
unig.st_dfm<-dfm(unig.st_tok)

unig2_tok<-tokens_ngrams(tok, n=2)
unig2_dfm<-dfm(unig2_tok)

Wordclouds can be constructed for visualising the most common words:

#wordcloud
textplot_wordcloud(unig_dfm, min_count=1200, random_order= FALSE, rotation = .25, color = RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"), labelsize = 10)

textplot_wordcloud(unig.st_dfm, min_count=750, random_order= FALSE, rotation = .25, color = RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"), labelsize = 10)

And the same can be done with pairs of words using the bigram:

#pairs of words
textplot_wordcloud(unig2_dfm, min_count=250, random_order= FALSE, rotation = .25, color = RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"), labelsize = 10)

The frequencies of words can also be plotted as follows:

#frequencies of words
feat_100<- textstat_frequency(unig_dfm, n=50)
feat_100$feature<-with(feat_100, reorder(feature, -frequency))
ggplot(feat_100, aes(x=feature, y=frequency))+geom_point()+theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, hjust=1))

Finally, the relative frequency of words from each source can be plotted. For informative purposes, the most common English words will be omitted. However, all words will be included in prediction models.

#relative frequencies of words by source
dfm_weight_source<- total.corpus %>%
  tokens(remove_punct = TRUE,
         remove_symbols = TRUE,
         remove_numbers = TRUE,
         remove_url = TRUE,
         split_hyphens = TRUE) %>%
  tokens_remove(bad) %>%
  tokens_remove(stopwords("english")) %>%
  tokens_keep(pattern = "^[a-zA-Z]+$", valuetype = "regex") %>%
  dfm() %>%
  dfm_weight(scheme = "prop")

freq_weight<-textstat_frequency(dfm_weight_source, n=10, groups = dfm_weight_source$source)
ggplot(data = freq_weight, aes(x = nrow(freq_weight):1, y = frequency)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ group, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = nrow(freq_weight):1,
                     labels = freq_weight$feature) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Relative frequency")
